by Baizou » Thu Apr 29, 2021 11:26 am

The Saucer Pilots wrote:snip

From reading their factbooks, I think I've learned that the Saucer Pilots are, as a society, relatively unambitious. That's not quite the right way to say it, as that makes it sound like they're lazy, which they're not. It's more like they're—modest. They don't crave conquest or expansion. Everyone works hard to be the very best comrade they can be, but one-upping colleagues is in-the-moment sport, not a matter of attaining permanent dominion over others. The Saucer Pilots may well be advanced enough to terraform the earth, and as much as terran living might be more comfortable, the Council (and the people generally it seems) just weren't that interested in it. They're rather have the amusement of humanity than control over the planet. Machinery intentionally deprecates to keep the Anhu employed, and it's created a sort of... again, stasis sounds too negative, because it makes it sound like the Pilots are stuck. I interpret it as being somehow Zen, though in a laidback way and not an ascetic sense. The Saucer Pilots are surprisingly content with what they have. They are livers, not takers; survivors, not breakers.

Representative Yutani chose to give himself quite possibly the most self-defeating name I have ever seen (though not most amusing, since I saw a news report edited by a girl named Megami of all things), and his outlook on life is true to his name as well. Yutani entered politics rather late in life, joining the libertarian party, though not out of fondness for Francine's misguided Randian outlook but rather a desire to avoid what he sees as a reenactment of past tragedies, instead opting to return to the world before globalisation and modernisation as reflected in his fondness for autarky and primitivism.

Imagine how much better his life would be if his parents had given him something generic like Kentaro.

by Baizou » Fri Apr 30, 2021 5:00 pm

The Saucer Pilots wrote:snip

I learned that Nova's name might be pronounced differently in the Anhu language. She is called "Nova" because her name appears to literally derive from stellar novas or supernovas. It's sorta like how Japanese and Chinese language(s) names get "translated" into each other—or at least, how I've been told they get translated into each other. Since Japanese and Chinese languages share characters with meanings that sometimes are also shared, I am told that characters are retained while pronunciations are changed to match the target language, as opposed to a transliteration as one might otherwise expect. That way, the name's meaning is retained, although the pronunciation is altered. I don't know if this is still how it's done, but it seems to be what happened to Nova.

Additionally, Nova apparently studied English for fourteen hours a day and thereby became fluent in two months! Dang, I guess biological engineering really did make the Anhu a bit of workaholics.
